segments.text: in the office in the 8th floor of the Rudder Tower and I have the pleasure and honor of chatting with Weldon Kruger.
Now I'm going to stop the machine and see if it's working.
A minute ago I did not get on the machine that this is March 24.
Weldon, why did you come to A&M in the first place?
What led you here instead of somewhere else?
Well, that's a good question.
I grew up in Brenham.
I wasn't sure I could go to college anywhere.
I didn't realize that you could really work your way through a place like A&M like you could back in those days.

And I was sort of oriented toward TU because my sister's husband, a veteran from World War II, was a student there, and they were particularly impressed with the university, I guess, and kept working on me.
But there's a fellow by the name of Howard Perry who worked for A&M for a long time in Utah not too many years ago.
He was a high school teacher of mine for a couple of years.
And he kept talking about A&M.
And I'm not sure whether he was the one in the end, but someone showed me or told me about the opportunity awards at A&M.
And I remember that I got the forms to fill out quite late.
I had to go over to the principal's house one evening
get him to sign it so I could get it in the mail on time.
And I won an opportunity award, and that was really, I guess, the final kicker that got me in this direction.
That big award was how much money?
Well, it was $1,000 over four years, so it was $250 a year, which was enough at that time to get me through school pretty well.
I worked during the summers, and with that and the opportunity award, I didn't have to work when I was here on the campus.
So that was good.
Had you been to visit the campus before you decided you wanted to attend here?
Well, as I say, I grew up in Brenham, so I'd been over here to the football games primarily.
I hadn't really visited any of the academic things.
I knew some other people at the Aggies.
I also had made up my mind the same year in high school I wanted to be an engineer, a civil engineer, because that's the only engineer I knew about.
Mainly I wanted to get some kind of education, and I wanted to go.
So I knew Anand had a great engineering experience.
This question won't be as meaningful to you as it is to other people.
When you came the first time to enroll, how did you get here?
Well, I came with a friend of mine from Brenham.
And I drove over.
My dad ran a business and had a truck.
And so he and I came over in that truck.
My dad was very sick that summer, and I was really running his business for him.
So anyway, a friend of mine from high school came over.
And I don't remember now whether we came to the campus, because we were going to be at the annex.
That year, the so-called Riverside Campus was annexed.
And I can't remember, but I think that's where we went and sort of signed up papers and everything.
And then a couple of weeks later, when it was actually time to come over here to start school,
his parents, both the two of us.
What did you bring when you came to stay?
What did you bring physically?
What items?
I didn't bring very much.
I had a footlocker because that was one of the things that they told us that we had to have in the barracks.
I didn't have really a very good, really wasn't a footlocker, it was sort of an oversized suitcase that I had.
So whatever was in that, I guess, was what I had.
I didn't have any
TVs or radios or anything like that.
I didn't need very much spare equipment.
No typewriter or anything like that?
No typewriter, no.
All right.
Please, because you're the first one we've chatted with about the Riverside campaign, about, you all called it the annex, didn't you?
The annex, yeah.
Yeah, yeah.
Give me as great a picture of the annex and life at the annex and the routine as you can.
Well, the annex was...
An air force base during World War II had been built, one of these temporary, I mean, I guess the government knew it wasn't going to last.
There were a series of barracks that were, we called them tarpaulin shacks, because the outside, well, they were wooden barracks, and the outside was covered with tarpaulin for the weather.
They were very substantially built, quite warm in the winter.
Behind the line of barracks were a line of latrines, and in the front was sort of a parade ground, and across from the parade ground was the assembly hall and a mess hall, several other buildings.
And then we were fairly close to the hangars and the flight line, the hard stand in front of the hangars and all that, and every now and then that's where we would go out and march.
But there was a road that went right down in front of all these barracks and that's where we had our morning and evening formations and march to the mess hall and that kind of thing.
How many and how many of whom were out there?
Well it was essentially all of the freshman class as far as students go.
There were of course obviously a staff and there were faculty members that taught the classes, a military staff.
I don't really know how many

freshmen there were but the only freshmen that were not out there were I suppose people that had maybe military veterans and athletes because that's why I remember meeting several of my classmates that were athletes living in Hart Hall and places that would come out on the weekends to see friends of them.
There were no sophomores?
There were no sophomores.
We had
The freshman class out there was organized into military units, very similar to the Corps here.
But we had our own officers.
We sort of rotated, being platoon leaders or flight leaders or squadron leaders, company leaders, whatever.
And they had a fish band out there that was formed, and you could start playing.
It was quite interesting.
We were bothered by sophomores and upperclassmen on weekends and other times.
I think they were restricted, if I remember right, as to when they could come out.
But I remember, I still remember a few names of particular ones that would come out, it seemed like, every weekend of the races.
Let's see, a fish drill team.
Didn't it get started out there?
Fish band and the fish drill team?
Yeah, I can't really remember.
I think there was a fish drill team.
Were there yell eaters?
Did y'all?
We had our own fish yell eaters, yeah.
We had our own.
Essentially, we followed the organization on the campus, but everything was done by freshmen.
And all the courses that freshmen took?
Every course I took that year, I took out there.
Do you remember what those courses were?
Well, I remember particularly taking English, 103 and 104.
And in one of those classes, I had a lady professor.
That was very unusual.
It was the only one I ever had while I was here.
Do you remember any of those teachers by name and qualities?
I don't remember any names.
I remember one professor that taught trigonometry.
that had sort of a different approach to it, and he told us what he was going to do, and I thought it was marvelous the way he would do it.

He told us that after about two weeks, he would go back and review what had been taught, and sort of, as he said, he found that people tend to lag behind the teacher sometimes, and they get completely lost.
Anyway, he was very nice, and I thought he was an excellent professor.
I can still sort of see him in my mind, but I don't remember his name at all.
Harrison Hurth was one of the English teachers I know out there.
They still live over here at Southside.
Happy Harry would be his later nickname.
I don't know whether...
There's a man by the name, I believe, of Randolph that was sort of the head of the freshman orientation program and gave a lot of the talks, and he's still out there.
But he was the one that said, I guess this is famous around here, but...
He told us one first week we were there, all right, everybody look to your right and look to your left.
And by the time you graduate, half of you will be gone.
Just make sure you're one of the ones that's still here.
So there was very little hazing.
Very little.
Y'all didn't do the duck walks and the push-ups and all that that would later be normal for freshmen.
No.
Push-ups and all that came much later.
We didn't do that kind of thing.
Describe a typical weekday, class day, from whenever getting up.
Go through a whole day describing it, please.
Well, I don't remember the time, but we were, I guess, awakened at a certain time in the morning by a bugle.
And I had a morning formation, marched off to ,, came back and took care of whatever we needed to do, and then went to our classes, which were all during the week, plus Saturday morning.
All the time I was at A&M, we had Saturday classes.
And it depended out there on what your class schedule was.
But they were all pretty compact, so you could move around pretty well from classroom to classroom.
It wasn't like the big campus here.
I do remember that it rained a heck of a lot.
We all issued these ponchos that we called moving pup tents.
And we had these helmet liners that we all issued.
So it seemed like it rained an awful lot that year.
Did you march to all meals?
I'm not sure about the noon meal.
I know we marched to morning and evening.
What did you all do in the afternoons if you weren't in class?
We had some core activities, core drills, just like they would at campus, like they do these days.
And if you were in the band, you had band practice.
You mentioned the fish drill team.
I think there was a starter one out there, and they did that.
Other than that, we would play ball, have our own little pick-up games, basketball and football in between the barracks.
That kind of thing.
What did you all do in the evenings once the sun went down?
Well, after the noon meal and once the sun went down, I'm not sure that's the exact time, but soon thereafter, we were supposed to be in the barracks studying, and we were.
And the, what we called attack officers, the military cavalry, they were out there and made sure that we were.
And they would come around and check on things.
And you were either in the barracks to study or you had to go out to the latrine.
That was an excuse.
And that went on until taps.
And then you had about 30 minutes to get yourself ready for bed and be in bed with the lights out.
And where did you all go on the weekends or any other time when you were off?
When could you legally be off that campus?
Legally, I'm not sure, but I think just on the weekends for court trips, we made those.
We were very much encouraged to make them.
I can't really remember for sure.
I didn't have a vehicle, a car.
Very few of us had a car when we were out there.
There were very few cars.
And I really didn't go.
So I can't really remember for sure what the restrictions were.
I do remember my dad passed away during that semester.
And I guess maybe because I was going to have to miss some classes, I remember going down and talking to the military advisor and giving them essentially a pass.
And I don't know whether he had to do that.
I'm sure you would have to do that to leave during the middle of the week.
I'm not sure about you.
All right.
Were there any kind of wild places where Aggie freshmen would go, whether legal or otherwise?
You know, I really... Where did somebody go to buy whiskey?
Buy whiskey?
Well, I think Brazos County was dry.
Mm-hmm.
And...
I don't remember anything across the bridge there on Highway 21, but there may have been something there.
You could go to Caldwell and get whatever they did.
I'm not sure they did.
That's a pretty good piece.
It wasn't like Whiskey Bridge out here on Highway 50.
I don't remember anything like that anywhere.
Now, did you all have Aggie slang?
out there for food?
Yeah, we were taught the typical Aggies course line that part of it's still used today.
But you all didn't whip out?
We whipped out.
We were taught to whip out.
No, but to each other out there?
We were taught pretty early on to whip out to each other, get to know all your classmates.
And we were certainly taught to whip out when the sophomores came out there on the weekend.
You know, in that whipping out business, of course, that's the real basis for it, going way back, is to get to know everybody.
Know where they're from and what they're taking, what their major is, that kind of thing.
But I wanted to say this earlier.
Looking back on it, and I've talked to a number of my classmates, our class is very close still.
We're coming up on our 45th reunion.
And a good part of that, I'm sure, is because we were all out there together.
We got to know practically every one of us, most everybody, as opposed to being scattered on the campus.
Even if you're in the Corps, you still don't get to know kids in the other units like you would when you're all out there and all those together.
Discuss the diversity in that group.
Were there any Hispanics?
There were a number of Hispanics in our class.
We didn't even think about diversity or minorities or anything.
It was just they were there, and they were good friends and good people.
Jewish?
I'm sure they were.
Yeah, in fact, I can think of a couple of those that were Jewish.
Any Asian, Chinese?
I don't remember any by appearance.
There may have been some with foreign extraction.
Any from another country?
I don't remember any foreign students at that time.
Let's see.
How did you all dress for class?
We dressed in the uniform of the day.
And, you know, I didn't realize until just a few months ago that there were some civilian freshmen out there with us.
And one boy that I ended up graduating with, I didn't realize it.
I knew he wasn't in the Corps the whole time.
I knew he had a physical disability.
But when he came back,

down here in Amon as a question with that disability, he and two or three friends of his, all from the same high school, convinced the authorities to let him come out there to the annex and be a part of everything and live with those other boys.
And they sort of watched him and took care of him and all that.
And so there were some civilians out there.
And he didn't wear a uniform?
He didn't.
He was not in the corps because he couldn't pass the visitation.
Can you describe any of the jokes or pranks or other good bull that you knew about during those days?
Well, let me see if I can remember the right chemistry here, but I remember one time I blew up one of the latrines by flushing something down the toilet.
And now I can't remember what the compound is, but it reacts pretty violently with water.
And all you've got to do is drop it in there and flush and run about as fast as you can do, I guess, to get out of it.
So that kind of thing went on.
Were there any tricks played on other students?
Yeah, there were always people that were mentioned earlier.
The so-called bulls, the military advisors, they were trying to keep all the things under control.
They had their hands full every now and then with one barracks trying to do something to the other barracks.
All good, clean phone, but
Now, did students out there have part-time jobs the way some on the campus did?
I'm sure some, yeah.
Some worked in the mess hall, I remember that.
But there weren't too many, you know, if you think about it, there weren't too many jobs out there.
I'm sure they worked a little bit with the ground maintenance crews and maybe even some of the repair crews, because like anything, you have to keep everything functioning.
Now, this was the fall of?
This would have been the fall of 1949.
And that, was that, how many years had that,
That wasn't the first year, was it?
That wasn't the first year, but it was the last.
Oh, it was the last year.
It was the last year because that air base was reactivated in the Korean War.
Then you came to the main campus as a sophomore.
Tell about being a sophomore in the Corps.
Okay.
I thought I was very lucky.
There was a...
a junior in what at that time was called H-Air Force.
It later became Squadron 10, a core unit.
And he came around talking to people.
He said, I want to have the best unit on the campus next year.
We want to win the General Moore trophy for the outstanding unit overall, academic, athletics, everything, marching, whatever.
And so he recruited.
with that in mind, and he made it known that, you know, if you wanted a bunch of bull, you weren't, you didn't need to come to that meeting.
And I've always looked back on that and thought, isn't that marvelous?
That guy had foresight, and we did win the general board that year, and two more years after that, three years running, and maybe beyond that, I don't know.
I don't want to find out about that, because I remember talking one time to
around Ray Bowen and mentioned Squadron 10.
And he said, well, I was in Squadron 10.
And I said, well, I don't know.
Class of 58?
And he said, well, you won the general military.
So I've got to do some checking on it.
But I know the three years I was in the Corps on the campus here, we won it.
And I look back and say it was all due to that fellow that really got it started.
Do you remember his name?
Doug Hearn, down over in Blanco or somewhere around Blanco or something like that.
Oh, now that might be important.
In those days, it was the Air Force.
It was just Army.
It was just Army.
And Air Force.
So already there were Army, I mean already there were Air Force.
Yes, yes.
It was about, I'd say, roughly maybe a third or a little bit much of Air Force and Army.
And the Army had all the branches.
They had artillery, armor.
How did the typical sophomore, your sophomore year, relate to freshman?

Well, okay, we came to the campus and we were, you might say, we were the freshmen in the units in the main corps because the annex was closed down, but they brought the freshmen in to the northern part of the campus and kept them separate from the rest of the corps, sophomores, juniors, and seniors that were

in what's called the new area in South Portland and they did have they did change though they they put a cadre of upperclassmen over with the freshmen and that went on the whole time that I was yeah even when my senior year that was still going on.
Did you sophomores get to
serve the juniors and seniors the way freshmen would have?
No, not in my particular unit.
There was some of that because we were the lowest classmen, and there was a little bit during meals and that kind of thing, but not very much.
So, as I say, my particular unit, our company commander and first sergeant were so intent on excellence in all things, they weren't too pushy on a lot of the little stuff that
All right, so then your unit didn't have much pranking and good bull and stunts?
We had some.
Do you remember any?
Do you remember any here on the campus that are tellable?

Well, you know, you always have the drown outs where somebody would come in your room and while you were asleep and gradually, sometimes gradually, sometimes just pour it on top of you, but usually just slide some water under you and let you sink in, that kind of thing.
I remember one time when there was some tear gas used in the dormitory.
And the deal there was you just, I don't know how people got tear gas, but you could just walk down the hall trailing it behind you and it took a while to vaporize and you'd be out of there before.
And then you look back and all the people were coming out of the door and was crying.
That kind of thing went on.
But we didn't do a lot of things like I heard about when you came.
Who were some of the memorable teachers, advisors, counselors, staff members that you remember from your student years?
Well, I remember, I mentioned earlier Howard Perry.
I remember he, I guess it was my sophomore year, he left Brenham and came over here and became a tack officer in the Corps.
And I thought he became quite popular because he just had the knack of working with people and working with cadets.
Some of the TAC officers weren't too popular, but he had the knack of giving you demerits and you'd smile about it.
A little bit later, the dean of engineering, a fellow named Barlow, Dr. Barlow, who left before I graduated, but he did a lot of things with the students and they all thought he was top-notch.
Of course, the president,
Tom Harrington, he's very well known.
Describe Dr. Harrington.
Well, Dr. Harrington was a tall, angular kind of guy, very friendly.
Had been a, I guess made his name in the first place as being an excellent chemistry professor.
But by the time I got to know him, he was a top administrator.
And I remember introducing him to my dad, who's now my wife,
She was from McKinney, and he said, oh, a Collin County girl.
And it turned out he had grown up in a little town of Plano up there.
So they got along just fine.
But I always liked Tom Harrington very much.
I thought he did an outstanding job.
Other faculty and staff?
Well, I don't remember.
Well, I do remember.
I sort of said I don't remember any sophomore
But I do remember a man that taught calculus in my sophomore year.
And again, I can't remember his name.
I can sort of see him in my mind.
But I thought he was an excellent teacher.
I can remember all the professors that I had over at Petroleum Engineering, because that was a fairly small department.
And there were four or five professors, essentially.
And I got to know them all very well.
And when I stayed over the next few years and got my master's, I got to know them even better.
So still.
Why did you pick petroleum engineering?
Well, I said way back there, I came over and wanted to be a civil engineer.
And I got this opportunity award.
And it was given by a man by the name of Toddy Lee Wynn from Dallas, who was in the petroleum bit.
And it was for a petroleum engineer, and that bothered me.
So I went to see E.E.
McQuillan, who had been around the campus forever.
He'd been the executive director of the Performing Students Association at one point.
At that time was, I don't know what all he was doing, but at least he was in charge of the scholarships.
So I went in to see Mr. McQuillan, and I said, I want to be a civil engineer.
not a petroleum engineer.
And this is for a petroleum engineer.
And he said, well, my understanding is that all engineering students take the same courses the first year, probably the first two years.
Is that right?
And I said, well, that's what I think that's right.
Well, why don't you just keep on going here, take those courses, and at the end, at some point, if you still want to be a civil engineer, we'll talk to Mr. Wynn about it and see what he did.
Well, just the fact that I had this thing
I got to looking around and thinking about petroleum.
I even went over and talked to some people in the petroleum department.
I got very interested in it and decided I went back to Mr. McClellan at the end of my freshman year and said, don't bother Mr. McClellan.
I'm happy.
I'm going to stay with petroleum and see how that goes.
I've never regretted that at all.
It turned out to be marvelous.
Do you remember any of the faculty nicknames?
Yes.
There were quite a few.
There was Cube Root Kent, Square Root Jackson.
The nicknames and why?
Well, I suppose those first two I mentioned were in the mathematics program.
I'm not sure of that.
I just remember the nickname.
There was another guy.
I won't even mention his last name, but he was known as Hose Nose for obvious reasons.
He had a big, long nose.
Another fellow, I won't mention his last name either.
He was called Plumbob because he was sort of shaped like Plumbob.
There were a number of names like that.
Did you have any of the history teachers that had those nicknames?
I don't think, I hate to tell you this, but I don't think I took a history course here.
In those days it wasn't required.
Well it was, but I took American history and I guess we have to take Texas history.
I took them by correspondence in the summer.
What were the rules
of classroom attendance and behavior that you and your fellow students assumed?
Well, attendance was very much encouraged by the different units in the Corps.
And I should say, some encouraged it very much, the one I was in very, very much, and others not so much, unfortunately.
But as far as if you were in the classroom,
The professors made damn sure that you were behaving yourself, let's say that.
Early on in some of the big lecture halls, chemistry and so on, two or three hundred students listening to a lecture, there were some people dozing and sleeping and whatever.
And I guess the professor couldn't see everybody.
But when you got into other classes, I know over in the petroleum department, if you nodded off, people walked down the aisle and waked you up.
Make sure you were listening.
Let's see, MSC, did it come into being?
The MSC opened, it seemed like it was my freshman year, but it may have been my sophomore year when we had the grand opening.
So we were very lucky to have that.
What role did it play in student life?
Well, it became sort of the living room of the campus, and that's the place you could go in.
or fight to eat in the cafeteria, a different kind of thing from the mess hall.
You could go there and the parents came and you could meet them there and take them there if they were here visiting.
A girlfriend came, that would be a place, this kind of thing.
It was also, at that time, we didn't have telephones in any of the rooms or any of the dorms, so if you wanted to make a telephone call or got a telephone call from somebody,
The messenger came to get you if you got one, and you'd go to MSC.
You had a bank of telephones there.
It was always very much used in MSC.
That's where you made your telephone calls.
And MSC activities, what was included in the activities within there?
Well, there was an MSC council, just like there is today.
And I remember Lamar McLuhan, my class, was an MSC council chairman.
I don't remember too much of the activities.
I wasn't, I guess, directly involved.
I wasn't on the council, I don't believe, my senior year.
And I wasn't too much directly involved.
I don't think it was just getting rolling, just getting started.
We didn't have the number of programs that we have now.
But we did have a cultural program called the Town Hall, which I think came under the MSC organization.
And I was on the Town Hall committee.
